    <a title="Raed" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/119247389-raed"><img alt="Raed" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1615454827p2/119247389.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/4326592362?book_show_action=true">Nov 20, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Raed" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Raed" href="/user/show/119247389-raed">Raed</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/119247389-raed?shelf=perpetually-reading">perpetually-reading</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer4326592362" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer14292287399921508072"><b>Is something sacred? Yes, say I with Nietzsche. I could not pray to it, but I can stand in affirmation of its magnificence. This world is sacred.</b><br/><br/>The truly dangerous aspect of Darwin&apos;s idea is its seductiveness.<br/><br/>My journey in evolution began with <b>Richard Dawkins and Jared Diamond </b> And I really liked the natural selection as an idea. Before reading this book i was thinking that evolution theory is like one of the most known tale in the world&apos;s folklore : <b>&quot;The Wolf in Sheep&apos;s Clothing&quot;</b> <br/>A tale of the</span>
  <span id="freeText14292287399921508072" style="display:none"><b>Is something sacred? Yes, say I with Nietzsche. I could not pray to it, but I can stand in affirmation of its magnificence. This world is sacred.</b><br /><br />The truly dangerous aspect of Darwin's idea is its seductiveness.<br /><br />My journey in evolution began with <b>Richard Dawkins and Jared Diamond </b> And I really liked the natural selection as an idea. Before reading this book i was thinking that evolution theory is like one of the most known tale in the world's folklore : <b>"The Wolf in Sheep's Clothing"</b> <br />A tale of the initially enemy mistaken for a friend, because i can never imagine that the Tree of Life created itself. i can never imagine a wonderful wedding of chance and necessity, happening in a trillion places at once, at a trillion different levels. And what miracle caused it? None. It just happened to happen, in the fullness of time.<br /><br />The Wolf in Sheep's Clothing here will give you an explanation but it will take from you the<br />meaning. The Meaning of life is the hardest question ever asked, and <b>Darwin</b> can't give you a meaning of life except the willing of life by natural selection.<br />I think the problem is not behind the Evolution Theory the problem is behind our quest for meaning. From that point The Wolf in Sheep's Clothing can become the Beast in the tale of <b>"Beauty and the Beast"</b>. Does Darwin's idea turn out to be, in the end, just what we need in our attempt to preserve and explain the values we cherish?<br /><br /> <u>Maybe the Beast is, in fact, a friend of Beauty</u><br /><br />I will add this book to my list of <b>"Perpetually reading"</b>:<br /><br />1-Thus Spoke Zarathustra <br />2-Until the End of Time<br />3-Darwin's Dangerous Idea<br /><br />I DON'T RECOMMEND THIS BOOK TO ANYONE, THIS IS NOT JUST "Darwin's Dangerous Idea" THIS IS A DANGEROUS BOOK.</span>
